{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525270"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:14:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:14:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14071"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14071"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.22,0.18,0.09,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6737"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42624"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2867"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40736"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of constant and dull lower abdominal pain. He has no associated symptoms. He has no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications. He drinks two glasses of wine on weekends and does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 128/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is some tenderness in the left iliac fossa, but the rest of the abdominal examination is unremarkable. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Analgesia only","Intravenous antibiotics","Colonoscopy","Percutaneous needle aspiration","Laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan of the abdomen shows an ovoid lesion adjacent to the descending colon with ring enhancement, having the density of fat and surrounding fat stranding. This pattern, together with the clinical picture, is consistent with a diagnosis of acute epiploic appendagitis. Epiploic appendages are small, fat-filled outpouchings of the distal colon and rectum. Although uncommon, these appendages can tort and become ischaemic, resulting in inflammation that causes pain and local tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalgesia only\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for epiploic appendagitis. This condition is typically self-limiting and resolves on its own, with pain relief being the primary treatment needed. Conservative management with analgesia allows the inflammation to subside naturally without unnecessary interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if another diagnosis, such as diverticulitis, was suspected. However, with the characteristic CT findings of epiploic appendagitis, antibiotics are not indicated as this is not an infectious process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would only be contemplated if the patient\u0027s problem was thought to be related to diverticular disease or if there was suspicion of a colonic neoplasm. In this case, with clear CT findings of epiploic appendagitis, colonoscopy is not necessary and would be an invasive overinvestigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if the lesion was thought to be cystic or an abscess. However, epiploic appendagitis is an inflammatory condition of a solid fat-containing structure, not a fluid collection, so aspiration is not appropriate and could potentially cause harm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E or any form of surgical intervention is not indicated for epiploic appendagitis. Surgery would be an unnecessary and invasive approach for a condition that resolves spontaneously with conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to managing epiploic appendagitis is recognizing its characteristic CT findings and understanding its benign, self-limiting nature. This allows for appropriate conservative management and avoids unnecessary invasive procedures or treatments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epiploic appendagitis is an uncommon cause of acute lower abdominal pain, with characteristic CT changes to clarify the diagnosis.","Epiploic appendagitis is typically a self-limiting condition that can be managed conservatively with analgesia alone.","CT findings of epiploic appendagitis include an ovoid lesion adjacent to the colon with fat density, ring enhancement, and surrounding fat stranding."],"references":["Giambelluca. D, Cannella R, Caruana G, et al. CT imaging findings of epiploic appendagitis: an unusual cause of abdominal pain. Insights Imaging. 2019; 10:26. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30796645/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42624"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14071"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20955"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21109"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20955"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ls5tRibRuGnnJYqVXyi2ZQfRpqXvbr.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ls5tRibRuGnnJYqVXyi2ZQfRpqXvbr.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":557,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21109"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PVIMf1eYPtNfRf0U4IpL0JVEkVt8pX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PVIMf1eYPtNfRf0U4IpL0JVEkVt8pX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":557,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42624"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T21:53:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T21:54:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6737"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"descrip